Con: If "country" isn't the single data point, then often the "human" is. These maps don't deal with population density.
Con: Many. many small countries are essentially invisible.
Con: If each country is a single data point, they should have similar weighting in terms of size.
Pro: You get a quick overview and data points are geographically related which might be important.

> x = [2,1,3]
> sort!(x)
> x
1
2
3

sort(x) leaves x unchanged.

log(e^A) = A, so the log likelihood also remove the exponential, making things easier still. #glm http://t.co/3t5oOD0wlT

So we look at the log likelihood. Like transforming data, if we find the maximum log likelihood then untransform it, we get the result. #glm

The probability of getting exactly 0.1 from a random number between 0 and 1 is zero, so we talk about density instead. #glm
In a continuous world we talk about probability density which doesn't relate to our typical understanding of probability. #glm
If we know the data we talk about likelihood of parameters. If we see 60 heads, what's the likelihood that the coin is fair i.e. 50/50? #glm
Likelihood is similar to probability. If we know the model parameters we talk about probability of data. P(heads) = 0.5 on a fair coin. #glm
#glm models work by writing a model then estimating the parameters using maximum likelihood.
